{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513128"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:05:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:05:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12017"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12017"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.65,0.02,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4597"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107700"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4597"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90132"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"2942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11061"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41438"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43287"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107700"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old woman, primigravida, presents to the Emergency Department at 28 weeks gestation with a blood pressure of 162/110 mmHg on two separate occasions. She reports a mild headache but denies any other symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy multivitamins and folic acid supplements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Neurological, abdominal and respiratory examinations are unremarkable. Urine dipstick is positive for proteinuria. Complete blood count, liver function tests, and coagulation studies are within normal limits. Ultrasound examination and uterine artery Doppler assessment are normal. Cardiotocography shows no signs of fetal distress.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV bolus magnesium sulfate","Oral nifedipine","Emergency caesarean section","Perindopril","Sodium nitroprusside"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe hypertension in pregnancy and proteinuria, diagnostic of pre-eclampsia. Pre-eclampsia is defined as new onset hypertension after 20 weeks gestation with proteinuria or evidence of end-organ dysfunction. Severe pre-eclampsia, as in this case with systolic blood pressure \u0026gt;160 mmHg, requires immediate pharmacological intervention due to the risk of serious complications such as eclampsia, intracerebral haemorrhage, and placental abruption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral nifedipine\u003C/strong\u003E is an appropriate first-line treatment for severe hypertension in pre-eclampsia. It is effective, safe in pregnancy, and can be easily administered. Other options include intravenous labetalol or hydralazine, but oral medications are preferred if the patient can tolerate them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV bolus magnesium sulfate\u003C/strong\u003E is used for seizure prophylaxis in severe pre-eclampsia or eclampsia. While it may be considered in this patient\u0027s management, it is not the most urgent first step. The priority is to lower her blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmergency caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E is not immediately necessary in this case. There are no signs of fetal distress, and the mother\u0027s condition can be managed medically. The goal is to stabilize the mother and prolong the pregnancy if possible, given the early gestational age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E, an ACE inhibitor, is contraindicated in pregnancy due to its teratogenicity. ACE inhibitors can cause fetal renal failure, oligohydramnios, and other congenital abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium nitroprusside\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely used in pregnancy due to the risk of fetal cyanide toxicity. It is reserved for hypertensive emergencies unresponsive to other treatments and when delivery is imminent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating antihypertensive therapy, this patient will require close monitoring, consideration of magnesium sulfate for seizure prophylaxis, and planning for timely delivery. The decision on timing of delivery will depend on gestational age, severity of pre-eclampsia, and maternal and fetal condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oral nifedipine should be commenced in pregnant women presenting with systolic blood pressure of \u003E160mmHg with signs of pre-eclampsia.","ACE-inhibitors are contraindicated in pregnant patients due to their teratogenicity.","Pre-eclampsia is diagnosed by new onset hypertension after 20 weeks gestation with proteinuria or evidence of end-organ dysfunction."],"references":["Lowe SA, Bowyer L, et al. Society of Obstetric Medicine of Australia and New Zealand. \u0027Guideline for the Management of Hypertensive Disorders of Pregnancy.\u0027 2014. Viewed October 2022. Available at: https://www.somanz.org/content/uploads/2020/07/HTguidelineupdatedJune2015.pdf","NICE Guideline. Hypertension in pregnancy: Diagnosis and Management. Available at: www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng133. 25 June 2019. Accessed 11/10/2022.","SA Maternal, Neonatal \u0026 Gynaecology Community of Practice. \u0027Hypertensive Disorder in Pregnancy\u0027. 2020. Viewed on September 2022. Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/aa782c004ee49dd483df8fd150ce4f37/Hypertensive+Disorders+in+Pregnancy_PPG_V5_2.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-aa782c004ee49dd483df8fd150ce4f37-ocQEdJI"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90132"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12017"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90132"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-02T09:44:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T21:53:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4597"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107700"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},